      "contextualized_query": "This is what we know so far:\n\n- Computational constraints limited some research, such as restricting fine-tuning to sequences up to 16K tokens due to GPU memory limitations.\n- Accurately counting words in text generated by LLMs is challenging because of the unique tokenization method employed.\n- Assessing the intrinsic consistency of Chain-of-Thought (CoT) reasoning paths in long-context language models is difficult and computationally expensive, even for models handling long inputs.\n- For simpler tasks, introducing CoT prompting may actually create interference.\n- LLMs can suffer from hallucination or including irrelevant content, requiring that reasoning paths be grounded in the actual source text.\n- Smaller-scale models may struggle to generate high-quality reasoning paths, and CoT might not benefit extremely easy retrieval tasks.\n\nNew question:\n\nHow does chain of thought impact the accuracy of CEFR generated text?",
      "query_output_path": "resoutputs/llm_weaknesses_refactor_check_t2_dbquery.md",
      "synthesized_summary": "The provided evidence does not directly address how Chain-of-Thought (CoT) impacts the accuracy of CEFR-generated text. However, research indicates that controlling linguistic features across different CEFR levels is challenging; for example, ChatGPT struggles to consistently match CEFR levels, with outputs tending to be either overly simple or overly difficult (Uchida, 2025).\n\nRegarding CoT, some findings suggest that it enhances multi-step reasoning tasks and provides benefits across most long-context scenarios, increasing with context length (Zhu et al., 2025). Conversely, introducing CoT prompting may create interference for simpler tasks (Zhu et al., 2025). Furthermore, the effectiveness of CoT varies by model size, as smaller models may not show consistent gains (Zhu et al., 2025).",
